01:49.228 --> 01:50.345
Hello.

01:50.379 --> 01:51.813
Welcome to Pawnee Videodome.

01:51.848 --> 01:53.181
Today we'll be screening

01:53.216 --> 01:56.635
Stanley Kubrick's 1957 classic
<i>Paths Of Glory.</i>

01:56.669 --> 01:59.337
It's about three men who refuse
to go on a suicide mission

01:59.372 --> 02:01.239
and are executed for cowardice.

02:01.274 --> 02:03.208
Or we could, you know,
maybe screen a different movie.

02:03.259 --> 02:04.976
One that's
a little bit more upbeat.

02:05.027 --> 02:06.394
Like <i>Finding Nemo</i> or...

02:06.429 --> 02:08.330
I could do, uh,<i>Shoah.</i>

02:08.364 --> 02:10.931
Okay,<i>Paths Of Glory</i> it is.

02:10.966 --> 02:12.584
This is the Pawnee Videodome.

02:12.618 --> 02:13.919
And we are here

02:13.970 --> 02:15.487
because I started a program
to help local business.

02:15.521 --> 02:17.389
This is a Pawnee institution.

02:17.423 --> 02:19.274
This is the place
where Perd Hapley

02:19.308 --> 02:22.210
shot his movie review show
<i>Lights, Camera, Perd.</i>

02:22.228 --> 02:25.097
It's a heartwarming story,
but it's just not believable.

02:25.131 --> 02:28.166
Which is why
I give <i>E. T.</i> 1 1/2 stars.

02:29.802 --> 02:31.970
Andy, it's over.

02:32.004 --> 02:33.472
Get up, Andy.

02:33.506 --> 02:34.756
What are you doing?

02:34.791 --> 02:35.957
What's everybody--
where are we?

02:35.992 --> 02:37.425
The reason I love that film

02:37.460 --> 02:39.277
is that it's really depressing.

02:39.312 --> 02:41.546
Speaking of which, sadly,
next month,

02:41.597 --> 02:44.082
Pawnee Videodome
will be closing its doors.

02:44.117 --> 02:46.001
- Forever.
- No!

02:46.035 --> 02:48.069
For those of you that
have attended our screenings,

02:48.103 --> 02:49.704
I want to thank you
for your patronage,

02:49.722 --> 02:52.357
though I wish you would have
rented more movies.

02:52.391 --> 02:54.843
Guys, we have to help out
Dennis and his business.

02:54.861 --> 02:56.978
Everybody rent something,
so we can help Dennis.

02:57.013 --> 02:58.112
Sir, will you rent something?

02:58.131 --> 02:59.181
Why would I do that?

02:59.215 --> 03:00.899
All movies are online
for free.

03:00.950 --> 03:02.818
I'm watching <i>Iron Man 2</i>
on my phone right now.

03:02.852 --> 03:04.252
Okay, you're not helping.

03:04.287 --> 03:06.671
I, for one, am going to rent
<i>Finding Nemo.</i>

03:06.706 --> 03:08.723
Ooh, we don't carry cartoons.

03:08.758 --> 03:10.675
But if you want a film
about the ocean,

03:10.710 --> 03:12.010
we have a documentary

03:12.061 --> 03:14.146
about the brutality
of Japan's whaling industry.

03:14.197 --> 03:15.914
It's called
<i>Tears Of My Blowhole.</i>

03:15.948 --> 03:17.232
And it's--it's nauseating.

03:17.266 --> 03:19.267
I'll just buy
some red vines.

03:19.302 --> 03:21.603
Oh, we only have
Japanese slime candy

03:21.637 --> 03:23.371
and, um, Bulgarian wheat balls.

03:23.406 --> 03:26.892
Leslie, seriously,
where are we?

03:26.926 --> 03:29.728
All these kids
have fathers

03:29.762 --> 03:31.780
and mothers
who have birthed them

03:31.814 --> 03:33.849
and are guiding them
through life.

03:34.383 --> 03:36.718
Yep, that's how it works.

03:36.752 --> 03:37.836
How are you feeling?

03:37.870 --> 03:39.905
Did you make
your dad-cision yet?

03:39.939 --> 03:41.489
I am 100% certain

03:41.524 --> 03:43.925
that I am 0% sure
of what I'm going to do.

03:43.959 --> 03:46.962
Ann Perkins asked me
if I would like to donate sperm,

03:46.996 --> 03:48.146
so she can have a baby.

03:48.181 --> 03:50.448
It's a battle
between my primal desire

03:50.499 --> 03:51.950
to bring a child
into this world

03:51.984 --> 03:53.485
and my paralyzing fear

03:53.519 --> 03:56.671
of negatively affecting
any living thing.

03:56.706 --> 03:58.273
There's $60 missing
from the register.

03:58.307 --> 04:00.125
I think Mona-Lisa's
stealing from me.

04:00.159 --> 04:01.743
Yeah, it is
absolutely Mona-Lisa.

04:01.761 --> 04:03.061
100%.
She's a total klepto.

04:03.095 --> 04:05.313
And nympho and pyro--
all those things.

04:05.331 --> 04:06.531
Okay, as your CFO,

04:06.582 --> 04:08.133
I recommend getting rid
of her immediately.

04:08.184 --> 04:09.968
I'm throwing
a huge cocktail party tomorrow

04:10.002 --> 04:11.152
for all my best clients.

04:11.187 --> 04:12.287
I don't have time
to find someone new.

04:12.321 --> 04:13.688
This sucks.

04:13.723 --> 04:16.007
You know,
when I was in high school,

04:16.041 --> 04:17.192
we had to spend a week

04:17.226 --> 04:18.760
carrying around
a sack of flour,

04:18.793 --> 04:20.028
pretending it was a kid.

04:20.062 --> 04:23.548
Why don't you
make Tom your sack of flour,

04:23.583 --> 04:26.234
see how it feels
to parent him a little?

04:26.252 --> 04:28.620
Ben, that is literally

04:28.654 --> 04:30.372
the greatest idea
in human history.

04:30.406 --> 04:32.540
I heard "sack of flour"
and "high school."

04:32.574 --> 04:34.859
Are you dingdongs making
fake drugs for sophomores?

04:34.894 --> 04:37.295
Because if true,
this guy wants in.

04:37.830 --> 04:40.198
Yeah, just have Mr. Traeger
call me when he gets back in.

04:40.233 --> 04:41.600
Actually, you know what?

04:41.634 --> 04:42.684
Don't tell him that I called.

04:42.718 --> 04:44.069
Just when he gets there,
can you text me

04:44.103 --> 04:45.070
and tell me he's back?

04:45.121 --> 04:46.404
You know what?

04:46.439 --> 04:47.889
Let's just pretend
this didn't happen, okay?

04:47.924 --> 04:49.925
This is Jerry Gergich calling.
Bye.

04:49.959 --> 04:51.776
I have to tell you
a secret.

04:51.811 --> 04:53.461
But if you tell anyone,

04:53.496 --> 04:55.747
I will kill you slowly
with a giant syringe.

04:55.781 --> 04:57.966
Good morning, April.
What's your secret?

04:58.000 --> 04:59.501
I'm thinking about applying
to veterinary school

04:59.535 --> 05:00.735
in Bloomington.

05:00.769 --> 05:02.637
Oh, my God, April,
that's great!

05:02.672 --> 05:04.506
Whoa!
Where'd you get that?

05:04.540 --> 05:06.024
The Internet.

05:06.058 --> 05:08.226
So I really need
a letter of recommendation.

05:08.261 --> 05:09.878
And since you work
in a hospital,

05:09.912 --> 05:11.296
- as a janitor...
- Nurse.

05:11.330 --> 05:15.200
I was wondering if maybe
you would write one for me?

05:15.251 --> 05:16.985
Really?

05:17.019 --> 05:18.019
Generally, between us,

05:18.054 --> 05:20.255
April always has
the upper hand.

05:20.289 --> 05:22.924
And that hand
is usually giving me the finger

05:22.959 --> 05:24.442
or pouring honey
in my purse.

05:24.477 --> 05:26.211
But now I have
the upper hand.

05:26.245 --> 05:27.529
And I'm going to use it

05:27.563 --> 05:29.180
to crush her...

05:29.215 --> 05:31.316
Into being nice
to me.

05:31.350 --> 05:33.685
I would be happy
to write you that letter.

05:33.719 --> 05:34.803
I actually know
the guy who runs

05:34.837 --> 05:36.021
the veterinary program
over there.

05:36.055 --> 05:37.622
Because you hooked up
with him?

05:37.673 --> 05:39.641
I don't hook up
with everyone I know.

05:39.675 --> 05:40.808
Although, yes,
we did hook up.

05:40.826 --> 05:42.243
But before I write you
that letter,

05:42.278 --> 05:44.346
you have to spend
the next week with me

05:44.380 --> 05:45.580
and do everything I say.

05:45.614 --> 05:47.499
So I have to be your slave
or something?

05:47.533 --> 05:49.317
No, you have to be
my friend.

05:49.352 --> 05:51.086
No, that is
so much worse.

05:51.120 --> 05:52.637
Don't do that.

05:52.672 --> 05:54.956
I think I have a plan
of how to save your store.

05:54.991 --> 05:57.375
If we get
the Pawnee Historical Society

05:57.410 --> 05:59.778
to declare your store
as a historical landmark,

05:59.812 --> 06:01.746
then you might get enough
of a tax break

06:01.781 --> 06:02.897
to keep your business afloat.

06:02.932 --> 06:04.265
That sounds
like the government

06:04.299 --> 06:05.984
meddling
in private enterprise.

06:06.035 --> 06:07.919
Well, Ron, we all know

06:07.953 --> 06:09.521
how much you love
the free market.

06:09.555 --> 06:13.074
But the Pawnee Videodome
is the only place in town

06:13.109 --> 06:14.909
where people gather
to do something intellectual.

06:14.944 --> 06:17.896
That and the slam poetry nights
at Beanie's Coffee.

06:17.947 --> 06:18.997
But I do not count those

06:19.031 --> 06:20.432
because those poems
do not rhyme.

06:20.466 --> 06:24.486
Anything can be a slam poem

06:24.520 --> 06:25.787
if you say it like this.

06:25.805 --> 06:27.072
It's pointless.

06:27.106 --> 06:28.623
This man is a failure.

06:28.657 --> 06:30.709
He is not up to snuff.

06:30.743 --> 06:32.743
His business is failing,
and you're bailing it out.

06:32.762 --> 06:34.713
This is a bailout,
and I don't like it.

06:34.747 --> 06:36.664
And there are some pretty
intellectual conversations

06:36.682 --> 06:38.383
down at Barrett's Hardware.

06:38.434 --> 06:40.618
You may get
a little heat for this, okay?

06:40.653 --> 06:42.654
So use
your money wisely.

06:42.688 --> 06:44.889
Get popular films
that people wanna see.

06:44.924 --> 06:46.474
Like, uh,

06:46.492 --> 06:48.727
get the Tarkovsky movies
<i>with</i> the subtitles.

06:48.761 --> 06:50.111
No. Like Pixar.

06:50.146 --> 06:51.379
Reese Witherspoon.

06:51.414 --> 06:52.514
I know this is gonna hurt,

06:52.548 --> 06:53.629
but maybe some Michael Bay.

06:53.632 --> 06:55.700
What? No, no.
No.

06:57.036 --> 06:59.287
Tom, I have something
I need to talk to you about.

06:59.321 --> 07:01.840
- Do we need to sit like this?
- Yes.

07:01.874 --> 07:03.658
Mona-Lisa's taking advantage
of you.

07:03.692 --> 07:05.310
And I'm sure
that it's not easy

07:05.344 --> 07:07.145
when it's the sister
of a dear friend.

07:07.179 --> 07:08.680
Oh, no, it's not that.

07:08.731 --> 07:10.014
She scares the crap
out of me.

07:10.049 --> 07:12.300
I once saw her punch
a police horse in the face.

07:12.334 --> 07:13.952
Speak directly to her

07:13.986 --> 07:17.605
and tell her,
"I will not be disrespected."

07:17.640 --> 07:19.224
You're Tom Haverford.

07:19.275 --> 07:21.793
You're a smart,
successful young man

07:21.827 --> 07:23.728
with an adorable,
little belly.

07:23.763 --> 07:25.180
Stand up for yourself.

07:25.214 --> 07:27.198
Yeah, I'll talk to her
before the party.

07:27.233 --> 07:28.500
And if she murders me,

07:28.551 --> 07:31.552
tell Jean-Ralphio
to clear my browser history.

07:31.570 --> 07:32.904
Thanks for the advice, man.

07:32.938 --> 07:34.722
You're welcome.

07:34.740 --> 07:35.840
Son.

07:35.875 --> 07:36.925
What's that?

07:36.959 --> 07:38.510
- Nothing.
- All right.

07:38.544 --> 07:40.245
Pawnee Videodome

07:40.279 --> 07:42.080
is where I rented
my first Bruce Lee movie.

07:42.114 --> 07:45.033
And my second Bruce Lee movie.

07:45.067 --> 07:46.701
And when I was
in seventh grade,

07:46.735 --> 07:48.686
I went out back
in the alley behind the store,

07:48.737 --> 07:50.989
and there was
a giant hornet's nest.

07:51.023 --> 07:53.658
And I threw a rock at it,
and it exploded.

07:53.692 --> 07:55.860
- And hornets came out.
- Andy-

07:55.911 --> 07:57.245
The point is,

07:57.279 --> 07:58.813
obviously,

07:58.831 --> 08:02.650
you do not throw rocks
at a hornet's nest.

08:02.668 --> 08:04.169
And the point is also

08:04.203 --> 08:06.287
that the Pawnee Videodome
is a place

08:06.321 --> 08:08.256
with tremendous community value,

08:08.290 --> 08:10.341
where people gather
to expand their horizons.

08:10.376 --> 08:12.427
Any other comments here
before we vo--

08:12.461 --> 08:13.878
Ron?

08:13.929 --> 08:15.430
What are you doing
at a city council meeting?

08:15.464 --> 08:17.665
Are you lost?
Are you hurt?

08:17.683 --> 08:19.551
No, I am here
to express an opinion.

08:19.602 --> 08:22.020
This action
by Councilwoman Knope

08:22.054 --> 08:23.238
is nothing more

08:23.272 --> 08:25.356
than a thinly veiled
government bailout.

08:25.391 --> 08:28.393
And I, for one, refuse
to let her turn this town

08:28.444 --> 08:30.228
into a socialist hellscape.

08:30.279 --> 08:31.679
Allow me to elaborate.

08:33.078 --> 08:36.679
The government should not
prop up a failed business.

08:36.804 --> 08:39.956
That would be like giving food
to a mortally wounded animal

08:39.974 --> 08:41.457
instead of slitting
its throat

08:41.476 --> 08:43.460
and properly utilizing
its meat and pelt.

08:43.494 --> 08:46.196
Please stop talking
about wounded meat.

08:46.230 --> 08:49.432
Pawnee needs a place
where the community can gather

08:49.467 --> 08:51.084
to discuss
and appreciate art.

08:51.119 --> 08:54.221
A place where you can rent
such films as <i>Cinema Paradiso</i>

08:54.255 --> 08:56.072
or <i>Rashomon.</i>

08:56.106 --> 08:57.224
You rented <i>Rashomon?</i>

08:57.258 --> 08:59.192
What was your favorite part
of that?

08:59.227 --> 09:00.794
I haven't rented it,
actually, yet.

09:00.828 --> 09:03.046
But I like the idea
that there is a place

09:03.080 --> 09:05.031
where I could rent <i>Rashomon.</i>

09:05.066 --> 09:07.033
Uh, you can
just watch it online,

09:07.084 --> 09:08.635
for free,
whenever you want.

09:08.669 --> 09:09.719
Bailiff!

09:09.754 --> 09:11.121
Thank you, Mr. Swanson,

09:11.155 --> 09:13.756
for your absurd opinion,
which is shared by no one.

09:13.774 --> 09:15.609
Now, are there
any more public comments

09:15.643 --> 09:18.645
before we vote?
Mm.

09:18.679 --> 09:20.430
How much to rent
this jacket?

09:20.464 --> 09:23.283
Oh. Curly Sue,
that jacket is so ugly.

09:23.317 --> 09:24.400
You should just take it.

09:24.418 --> 09:25.785
It's 15 for the day,

09:25.837 --> 09:26.920
40 for the week.

09:26.954 --> 09:28.171
Thank you.

09:28.189 --> 09:29.523
We appreciate your business.

09:29.557 --> 09:31.041
Mona-Lisa!

09:31.075 --> 09:32.576
Did you order the champagne
for the client party tonight?

09:32.610 --> 09:35.328
Did I order the what
for the what-what what, what?

09:35.363 --> 09:37.631
What are you even talking about
right now?

09:37.682 --> 09:39.432
Okay, we need
to discuss your work habits.

09:39.467 --> 09:41.518
Okay, sure,
but after I take a quick nap

09:41.552 --> 09:44.070
because ecstasy takes

09:44.121 --> 09:46.373
♪ forever to leave my system

09:46.424 --> 09:49.225
No. We're doing this now.

09:49.243 --> 09:50.877
You need to start putting in
more of an effort

09:50.912 --> 09:52.646
and start respecting
my authority around here!

09:52.680 --> 09:53.630
Or else what?

09:53.648 --> 09:55.982
Or else I'll fire you.

09:56.033 --> 09:57.300
What did you just say?

09:57.335 --> 09:59.369
I said, if you don't shape up,
I'll fire you.

09:59.387 --> 10:00.487
Do you understand?

10:01.021 --> 10:03.073
You are so freaking sexy
right now,

10:03.107 --> 10:04.124
I could crap my pants.

10:04.158 --> 10:05.959
Ugh.

10:06.010 --> 10:07.243
What are you doing?

10:08.346 --> 10:09.980
I guess
it would have to be

10:10.014 --> 10:11.464
Channing Tatum's body,

10:11.499 --> 10:13.400
Ryan Gosling's face,

10:13.434 --> 10:16.920
and Michael Fassbender's...
sense of humor.

10:16.954 --> 10:18.188
What about you?

10:18.222 --> 10:19.188
Build your perfect guy.

10:19.207 --> 10:20.156
Um...

10:20.174 --> 10:21.758
Yao Ming's torso,

10:21.976 --> 10:23.243
Napoleon's brain,

10:23.277 --> 10:25.812
and The Hunchback
of Notre Dame's hunchback.

10:25.846 --> 10:26.947
Do you like my nails?

10:27.681 --> 10:29.032
Even though she hides it

10:29.050 --> 10:31.668
underneath layers of sarcasm,
resentment, and grumpiness,

10:31.702 --> 10:33.587
I know,
deep down somewhere,

10:33.638 --> 10:35.138
April likes me.

10:35.172 --> 10:37.474
I'm kind of just fracking
for friendship.

10:37.508 --> 10:40.443
Gene Strackwell,
owner of Strackwell Hardware.

10:40.478 --> 10:43.163
Is there a form I need
to fill out for the bailout?

